TI  - The role of internal labour markets and social networks in the recruitment of top managers in Finnish manufacturing firms, 1900-1975
T2  - BUSINESS HISTORY
AB  - In this article, the recruitment of top industrial managers in large manufacturing firms in Finland is studied. Between 1900 and 1975 industrialisation was rapid and management in big business professionalised. This was reflected in radical changes in the managerial profile, particularly with respect to educational and career backgrounds, but also in the recruitment process. However, as recruitment of managers is also a result of institutional and historical factors, of corporate culture and of corporate traditions, the recruitment also showed some persistent features. During the whole period of investigation, Finnish managers were primarily recruited on internal labour markets. Top managers were recruited from within a limited group of potential candidates. Social networks formed an important basis for these internal labour markets, but the type of networks changed as a consequence of industrialisation, bureaucratisation and professionalisation.
