T2  - INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF URBAN AND REGIONAL RESEARCH
AB  - The purpose of this paper is to examine the interrelated sequence of events that leads to early motherhood among impoverished African-American women in West Baltimore, an urban area whose rates of teenage pregnancy are pore than triple those of the United States as a whole. Conservative assessments of the problem see adolescent pregnancies as the effect of deviant values promoted by welfare programmes. Liberal approaches have been more likely to emphasize macroeconomic factors as the cause of poverty and early motherhood. Both views agree, however, that adolescent pregnancy and motherhood increase the probability of persistent poverty. Neither of the two views explains the reason why impoverished women are more likely to take pregnancies to term than their more affluent counterparts. By resorting to recent conceptualizations in the new economic sociology, and on the basis of testimonies provided by 27 women - all of them members of a larger sample formed by 50 impoverished African-American families - I argue that, in the absence of resources facilitating integration into the labour market, young women seek self-individuation, rank and status by becoming mothers. Motherhood thus becomes an avenue to achieve social standing and adulthood in social networks characterized by impoverishment and isolation from the larger society.
