AU  - SMITH, MP
AU  - TARALLO, B
AU  - KAGIWADA, G
TI  - COLORING CALIFORNIA - NEW ASIAN IMMIGRANT HOUSEHOLDS, SOCIAL NETWORKS AND THE LOCAL STATE
T2  - INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF URBAN AND REGIONAL RESEARCH
AB  - When faced with the formation of economic and political interests household members confront three basic options - work, voice or exit. These choices are unavoidably embedded in the social relations of the home, as well as in the relations between households, social classes, men and women and other ethnic groups. The social practices analysed in this article are drawn from our ethnographic interviews with representatives of public and private social service agencies. community organizations, and new Chinese immigrant and Southeast Asian refugee household members in three neighbourhoods in Sacramento. California. Our study reveals that social networks based on ethnicity and kinship are a crucial form of agency in the survival of new immigrants and refugees, particularly in the current period of fiscal austerity. While first-wave Vietnamese refugees are generally highly self-sufficient, second-wave boat people rely heavily on public services. Because of recent cutbacks in services, they also engage in newly created informal patterns of survival not easily facilitated through government-funded programmes. These include small businesses which are often ethnic reproductions of businesses of the home country mediated by their experiences in the American cultural context. Most new Chinese immigrants rely heavily on existing social networks in the established ethnic community in finding employment. As a result, they often end up doing low-skilled work in small ethnic businesses in the 'enclave economy' where the Asian language is spoken, especially in restaurants and garment shops. Although work in such enterprises fosters intra-ethnic solidarity and avoids discrimination from non-Asians, it may facilitate an exploitative ethnic economic enclave, masked by cultural familiarity, but economically as alienating for workers as the mainstream secondary labour market. In sum, both cutbacks in governmental assistance programmes and the operation of ethnic informal social networks tend to channel immigrants and refugees into a marginal labour sector increasingly in demand due to the restructuring of the world economy. The irony of this overall pattern is that social regulation to incorporate newcomers into the economy and other institutional processes actually creates a context whereby newcomers are forced to rely on their own resources for action.
