T2  - SOCIOLOGICAL SPECTRUM
KW  - STATES
AB  - This study used a sociohistorical approach to explore various ways in which contextual and institutional factors changed the labor market for Methodist clergy between 1940 and 1980 in Oklahoma. Specifically, this study focused on how a significant shift of population from rural to urban areas and from city to suburban areas in Oklahoma between 1940 and 1980 was mediated by new church development policies and the social network nature of congregations to influence the number and salaries of Methodist clergy positions. Second, this study examined how institutional and population factors affected the structure of the internal market for Methodist clergy It was found that (1) a secondary market exists for clergy, which is used to deal with variations in the growth and decline of both the numbers of clergy positions available in the state and the number of persons who are full member clergy, (2) seniority plays a larger role in the appointment of clergy under different sets of rules governing a bishop and under different bishops, (3) clergy who transfer into the conference under conditions of rapid population growth and inadequate clergy supply from within the conference were able to obtain higher salaries in their initial appointment than persons who entered the conference from within or who transferred into the conference during a period of negative or flat church growth, and (4) a small cohort of clergy associated with World War II followed by several years of large cohorts entering the ministry combined with the seniority policies of bishops to affect the survival of clergy in the ministry from one time period to another.
