AB  - Objective. Research has begun to show that social ties influence the ways in which immigrants find jobs in a host community. This research investigates how social ties affect immigrants' employment status and wages, and how these effects may depend on community social-class composition. Methods. Data used are from a pilot survey of Salvadorean and Pilipino immigrants in two Los Angeles communities. Analyses are conducted with probit models and ordinary least squares regression models corrected for selection. Results. The findings, unlike those in many previous studies, show that strong social ties, such as family ties, affect employment status and wages. The effects, however, differ by gender. Among men, working with relatives is associated with higher wages. Among women, having non-coresident relatives in the United States is associated with higher wages. The latter finding is most plausibly a social-network effect among Salvadorean women, who live in a working-class community. Conclusions. These findings suggest that social ties are important determinants of the wage-earning potential of immigrants, and that the effects of social ties depend on community characteristics such as social-class composition.
